<h1>Diagram 2 — Deployment Diagram</h1>

<h2>Purpose</h2>
<p>
  Shows the physical deployment topology: where each service runs, how traffic reaches
  the API from outside (Cloudflare Tunnel), and the monitoring stack that watches the
  system.
</p>

<h2>Mermaid Source</h2>
<pre>
flowchart TB
    Users["Users / Employees\n(any location)"]

    Users --> V["Vercel Edge\nNext.js Frontend\nerp-dusky-six.vercel.app"]
    Users --> CF["Cloudflare DNS\n+ Tunnel"]

    CF --> Caddy["Caddy Reverse Proxy\n(custom Alpine image, TLS,\nsecurity headers, UID 10001)"]

    subgraph DockerServer ["Local Docker Server (Pratham's machine)"]
        Caddy --> API["FastAPI api\n(UID 10001, Alpine)"]
        API --> REDIS["Redis\n(auth enabled,\ninternal network only)"]
        REDIS --> WORKER["Celery worker\n(UID 10001, Alpine)"]
        REDIS --> SCHED["Celery scheduler\n(UID 10001, Alpine)"]
    end

    API --> SUPA["Supabase Cloud\nAuth + PostgreSQL\n+ Storage"]
    WORKER --> SUPA
    SCHED --> SUPA

    subgraph Monitoring ["Monitoring Stack"]
        UK["Uptime Kuma\n(Raspberry Pi)"] -. monitors .-> V
        UR["UptimeRobot"] -. monitors .-> V
        CFA["Cloudflare Tunnel\nAlerts"] -. alerts .-> CF
        DZ["Dozzle"] -. log viewer .-> DockerServer
    end

    style DockerServer fill:#EAF5EA,stroke:#27AE60
    style Monitoring fill:#FFF8E1,stroke:#F39C12
    style REDIS fill:#FADBD8,stroke:#E74C3C
</pre>

<h2>Key Points</h2>
<ul>
  <li>The Next.js frontend is hosted on Vercel's global edge network; no backend containers are needed for frontend serving.</li>
  <li>The FastAPI backend runs locally in Docker on Pratham's machine and is exposed to the internet only through a Cloudflare Tunnel — no ports are forwarded on the router.</li>
  <li>Redis is on an internal Docker network and is not reachable from outside the Docker host; Redis authentication is enforced in production.</li>
  <li>All containers run as non-root (UID 10001); the custom Caddy image is source-compiled from alpine:3.24 and passes Docker Scout at 0 critical/0 high CVEs.</li>
  <li>Uptime Kuma (self-hosted on Raspberry Pi) and UptimeRobot provide redundant public monitoring with email alerts to Pratham as the incident contact and rollback owner.</li>
</ul>

