<h1>Diagram 5 — Document Upload &amp; Download Flow</h1>

<h2>Purpose</h2>
<p>
  Shows how documents are securely uploaded to private Supabase Storage through
  FastAPI validation, and how downloads use short-lived signed URLs to avoid
  exposing raw Storage paths.
</p>

<h2>Mermaid Source</h2>
<pre>
sequenceDiagram
    participant User as 👤 User
    participant Web as Next.js Frontend
    participant API as FastAPI Backend
    participant Storage as Supabase Storage (private)
    participant DB as Supabase PostgreSQL

    Note over User,DB: UPLOAD FLOW

    User->>Web: Select file in upload dialog
    Web->>API: POST multipart/form-data\n(file + metadata)
    API->>API: Validate JWT + RBAC + ABAC
    API->>API: Validate filename, MIME type, size
    API->>Storage: Upload to private bucket\n(immutable key, never overwritten)
    API->>DB: INSERT document record\n+ document_version record
    API->>DB: Store SHA-256 checksum\n+ immutable storage key
    API->>DB: Write audit event\n(actor, action, resource, timestamp)
    API-->>Web: DocumentResponse (metadata only)

    Note over User,DB: DOWNLOAD FLOW

    User->>Web: Click download
    Web->>API: GET /v1/document-versions/{id}/download-url
    API->>API: Validate JWT + authorization
    API->>Storage: Generate short-lived signed URL\n(expires in minutes)
    API-->>Web: Signed URL
    Web->>Storage: Browser downloads directly from signed URL
</pre>

<h2>Key Points</h2>
<ul>
  <li>Files are never stored on the FastAPI server; they are streamed directly to Supabase Storage using the service-role key, which exists only on the backend.</li>
  <li>Storage keys are immutable — a new document version always creates a new storage object; existing objects are never overwritten, preserving full version history.</li>
  <li>Download URLs are short-lived signed URLs generated by FastAPI after checking authorization; the browser downloads directly from Supabase Storage CDN without any round-trip through FastAPI.</li>
  <li>Server-side validation checks filename (no path traversal), MIME type (against allowed list), and file size before any Storage write occurs.</li>
  <li>SHA-256 checksums are stored in the database for every document version, enabling integrity verification.</li>
</ul>

<div class="evidence">
  <strong>Evidence files:</strong>
  docs/api-contract.md &nbsp;|&nbsp; docs/04_SECURITY_MODEL.md &nbsp;|&nbsp;
  apps/api/app/api/v1/documents_archive.py &nbsp;|&nbsp;
  apps/api/app/services/documents_archive.py &nbsp;|&nbsp;
  apps/web/src/lib/api.ts &nbsp;|&nbsp;
  supabase/migrations/202606040005_folders_documents.sql &nbsp;|&nbsp;
  supabase/migrations/202606040015_storage.sql
</div>

<!-- ============================================================ -->
<h1>Diagram 6 — Archive Export Flow</h1>

<h2>Purpose</h2>
<p>
  Shows how project archive exports (ZIP files with folder hierarchy, manifest, and
  index PDF) are generated asynchronously by a Celery worker and made available via
  a signed download URL.
</p>

<h2>Export Status State Machine (Mermaid)</h2>
<pre>
stateDiagram-v2
    [*] --> QUEUED : User requests export
    QUEUED --> GENERATING : Celery worker picks up job
    QUEUED --> CANCELLED : User cancels before generation starts
    GENERATING --> READY : ZIP uploaded to Storage successfully
    GENERATING --> FAILED : Worker encounters unrecoverable error
    READY --> EXPIRED : TTL cleanup job runs
    READY --> [*] : User downloads archive
</pre>

<h2>Archive Generation Flow (Mermaid)</h2>
<pre>
flowchart TD
    User["User requests archive export"] --> API["FastAPI creates\narchive_export row\nstatus = QUEUED"]
    API --> Redis["Dispatch Celery job\nvia Redis broker"]
    Redis --> Worker["Celery worker picks up job\nstatus -> GENERATING"]
    Worker --> Meta["Read folder + document\nmetadata from PostgreSQL"]
    Worker --> Files["Download private documents\nfrom Supabase Storage"]
    Worker --> ZIP["Build ZIP file\n(preserving folder hierarchy)"]
    ZIP --> PDF["Generate manifest\n+ index PDF"]
    PDF --> Upload["Upload ZIP to\ngenerated-archives bucket"]
    Upload --> Ready["Mark export READY\nin PostgreSQL"]
    Ready --> Notify["Create employee notification"]

    User2["User polls for export status"] --> Status["GET /v1/exports/{id}\nstatus: QUEUED / GENERATING / READY"]
    Status --> DL["GET /v1/exports/{id}/download-url\n(only when READY)"]
    DL --> SignedURL["FastAPI generates\nshort-lived signed URL"]
    SignedURL --> Download["Browser downloads from\nSupabase Storage"]

    style Ready fill:#D5E8D4,stroke:#27AE60
    style Upload fill:#D5E8D4,stroke:#27AE60
</pre>

<h2>Key Points</h2>
<ul>
  <li>Export generation is fully asynchronous — the API returns immediately with status QUEUED and the frontend polls until the status changes to READY.</li>
  <li>The Celery worker reconstructs the folder hierarchy inside the ZIP, preserving the IEMS folder naming convention (e.g., 01 Client Brief/, 04 Venue Documents/) in the archive.</li>
  <li>A manifest file and index PDF are generated automatically and included in every archive export.</li>
  <li>Exports can be cancelled while QUEUED; attempting to cancel a GENERATING or READY export returns 422 INVALID_STATE.</li>
  <li>READY exports expire after a configured TTL; expired exports return a signed-URL-not-available error and must be re-requested.</li>
</ul>

<div class="evidence">
  <strong>Evidence files:</strong>
  docs/api-contract.md &nbsp;|&nbsp;
  apps/api/app/api/v1/documents_archive.py &nbsp;|&nbsp;
  apps/api/app/services/documents_archive.py &nbsp;|&nbsp;
  compose.yaml &nbsp;|&nbsp;
  supabase/migrations/202606040006_archive_exports.sql &nbsp;|&nbsp;
  supabase/migrations/20260606155127_cancel_archive_export.sql
</div>

<!-- ============================================================ -->
<h1>Diagram 7 — Physical Archive Flow</h1>

<h2>Purpose</h2>
<p>
  Shows how the physical records-room hierarchy is set up, how physical files are
  registered and QR-labelled, and how checkout/return/verify operations maintain the
  audit trail.
</p>

<h2>Mermaid Source</h2>
<pre>
flowchart TD
    subgraph Setup ["Archive Room Setup (Admin)"]
        Room["Archive Room\n(e.g. Records Room A)"]
        Room --> Rack["Rack\n(e.g. R02)"]
        Rack --> Shelf["Shelf\n(e.g. S03)"]
        Shelf --> Cabinet["Cabinet\n(optional)"]
        Cabinet --> Box["Box\n(e.g. B05)"]
        Box --> Slot["File Slot\n(e.g. F014)"]
    end

    subgraph Registration ["Physical File Registration"]
        Project["Project\n(e.g. IEMS-2026-0042)"] --> Register["Register physical file\nPOST /v1/projects/{id}/physical-files"]
        Register --> QR["QR token generated\nGET /v1/physical-files/{id}/label"]
        QR --> Label["Printable label\n(Project ID + location + QR code)"]
        Register --> Slot
    end

    subgraph Lifecycle ["File Lifecycle Operations"]
        Available["Status: AVAILABLE"] --> Checkout["Checkout request\n(employee, purpose,\nexpected return date)"]
        Checkout --> CheckedOut["Status: CHECKED_OUT\n+ checkout row created\n+ audit event"]
        CheckedOut --> Return["Return request\n(returned_at set)"]
        Return --> Available

        Available --> Move["Move to new location"]
        Move --> Available

        Available --> Verify["Verification scan\n(confirm exists,\nlabel readable, location correct)"]
        Verify --> Available
        Verify --> Audit2["last_verified_at updated\n+ audit event"]

        CheckedOut --> Overdue["OVERDUE flag\nif past expected return\n(visible on Director Dashboard)"]
    end

    subgraph QRScan ["QR Scan Resolution"]
        Scan["Employee scans QR code"] --> Resolve["GET /v1/physical-files/by-qr/{qr_token}"]
        Resolve --> FileDetail["Redirect to /archive/files/{id}"]
    end

    style Available fill:#D5E8D4,stroke:#27AE60
    style CheckedOut fill:#FFF3CD,stroke:#F39C12
    style Overdue fill:#FADBD8,stroke:#E74C3C
</pre>

<h2>Key Points</h2>
<ul>
  <li>The physical archive hierarchy mirrors the digital folder system: every physical file is linked to a project ID, creating a single source of truth across both digital and physical records.</li>
  <li>QR codes are generated per physical file and encode an opaque token (not a Storage URL or auth secret). Scanning redirects to the file detail page after API resolution.</li>
  <li>The checkout register tracks the employee, purpose, expected return date, and actual return date; overdue files are surfaced on the Director Dashboard.</li>
  <li>All physical file operations (checkout, return, move, verify) write immutable audit events with the actor, action, and timestamp.</li>
  <li>The QR scan route (/archive/scan/[qr_token]) is accessible from any device with a browser, allowing physical scanning without a dedicated app.</li>
</ul>

