<h1>Diagram 10 — Module Rollout Flow</h1>

<h2>Purpose</h2>
<p>
  Shows how phased module enable/disable works across the backend environment flags,
  the /v1/modules API endpoint, and the frontend gating layer — with the backend
  middleware as the authoritative enforcement point.
</p>

<h2>Mermaid Source</h2>
<pre>
sequenceDiagram
    participant Env as Backend .env\nMODULE_*_ENABLED flags
    participant API as FastAPI Settings\n+ Middleware
    participant Modules as GET /v1/modules\n(unauthenticated)
    participant Web as Next.js Frontend
    participant Sidebar as Sidebar Component
    participant Guard as ModuleGuard Component
    participant Route as Protected API Route

    Note over Env,API: At process startup
    Env->>API: Load all MODULE_*_ENABLED flags
    API->>API: FastAPI Settings validates and stores flags

    Note over Web,Guard: On page load
    Web->>Modules: Fetch module list (no auth required)
    Modules-->>Web: [{code: "projects", enabled: true}, ...]
    Web->>Sidebar: Filter nav items by enabled flags
    Sidebar-->>Web: Hide disabled module links
    Web->>Guard: Render page content
    Guard-->>Web: Show ModuleDisabledState if module disabled

    Note over Web,Route: When user accesses a page or calls API
    Web->>Route: API call to disabled module route
    Route-->>Web: 403 MODULE_DISABLED\n"This module is not enabled for this rollout."

    Note over Env: To enable/disable a module
    Env->>API: Update .env flag
    API->>API: Restart uvicorn process\n(docker compose up --force-recreate)
    API->>Modules: New flag state served immediately
</pre>

<h2>Module Flag Configuration</h2>
<table>
  <tr><th>Flag</th><th>Current .env</th><th>Recommended Onboarding</th></tr>
  <tr><td>MODULE_PROJECTS_ENABLED</td><td>true</td><td>true</td></tr>
  <tr><td>MODULE_DOCUMENTS_ENABLED</td><td>true</td><td>true</td></tr>
  <tr><td>MODULE_ARCHIVE_EXPORTS_ENABLED</td><td>true</td><td>false (enable after training)</td></tr>
  <tr><td>MODULE_PHYSICAL_ARCHIVE_ENABLED</td><td>true</td><td>false (enable after physical setup)</td></tr>
  <tr><td>MODULE_ATTENDANCE_ENABLED</td><td>false</td><td>false (enable when HR ready)</td></tr>
  <tr><td>MODULE_LEAVE_ENABLED</td><td>false</td><td>true</td></tr>
  <tr><td>MODULE_TASKS_ENABLED</td><td>true</td><td>true</td></tr>
  <tr><td>MODULE_CALENDAR_ENABLED</td><td>true</td><td>true</td></tr>
  <tr><td>MODULE_APPROVALS_ENABLED</td><td>true</td><td>true</td></tr>
  <tr><td>MODULE_DIRECTOR_DASHBOARD_ENABLED</td><td>true</td><td>true</td></tr>
  <tr><td>MODULE_ADMIN_ENABLED</td><td>true</td><td>true</td></tr>
</table>

<h2>Key Points</h2>
<ul>
  <li>The backend is the sole source of truth for module state. The Vercel frontend does not need any module-specific environment variables — it reads /v1/modules at runtime.</li>
  <li>The frontend module gating (sidebar hiding, ModuleGuard) is UX-only and provides no security guarantee; the FastAPI middleware blocks disabled API routes with 403 MODULE_DISABLED before any business logic runs.</li>
  <li>The /v1/modules endpoint is intentionally unauthenticated so the frontend can fetch module state before the user logs in, enabling correct login-page rendering.</li>
  <li>The frontend fails open: if /v1/modules is unreachable (network error or non-200 response), all modules are treated as enabled to prevent user lockout during a backend outage.</li>
  <li>To change module flags in production, update the .env file and run: docker compose up -d --force-recreate api worker scheduler</li>
</ul>

